  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Public Healthcare Will Cover You</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Work visa holders have limited access to subsidized public healthcare. You'll pay full price for GP visits (NZ$50-80) and face long waits for specialists. Get private insurance before arriving—don't wait until you need care.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Checking Employer Accreditation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Only accredited employers can hire AEWV workers. If your employer isn't accredited, they must apply first—this adds 2-4 weeks. Ask about accreditation status before accepting an offer. Check the employer accreditation list online.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Leaving Police Certificates Too Late</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Some countries take 8-12 weeks for police certificates. You need clearances from every country you've lived in for 5+ years since age 17 (for stays over 24 months). Start these requests immediately when you decide to apply.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Understanding the Median Wage Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Most AEWV roles require at least NZ$31.61/hour (median wage). This is about NZ$65,700/year full-time. Some occupations have exemptions, but check before assuming your offer qualifies. Below-threshold offers get rejected at Job Check.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Qualification Verification</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For regulated professions (engineering, nursing, teaching, etc.), you must register with NZ professional bodies BEFORE applying. This can take months. Don't accept a job offer until you understand the registration timeline and requirements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in New Zealand -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in New Zealand</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      New Zealand has a two-tier healthcare system: public (government-funded) and private. Work visa holders have limited public access but can use private healthcare with insurance. The unique ACC system covers all accidents regardless of visa status.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How New Zealand Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">General Practitioners (GPs)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register with a local GP clinic. Work visa holders pay NZ$50-80 per visit (residents pay ~NZ$20). With private insurance, you can claim most of this back. After-hours clinics cost more. Book appointments online or by phone.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Public Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Emergency departments are free for everyone. Inpatient hospital care is free if admitted. But the issue is waiting lists—elective procedures can take months or years. Private insurance gives access to private hospitals with shorter waits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Public specialist appointments have long waiting lists (often 6+ months). Your GP refers you. With private insurance, you can see private specialists directly, usually within weeks. This is the main reason expats get insurance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">ACC (Accidents)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">ACC covers all accidents for everyone in NZ—no exceptions. If you're injured in any accident, treatment is covered. ACC also provides income replacement (80% of salary) if you can't work due to injury. This is funded by levies, not insurance premiums.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Finding Doctors</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Register with a GP clinic near your home or work—you need to enroll to access subsidized rates (when eligible). Use healthpoint.co.nz to find clinics. In Auckland and Wellington, many practices are accepting new patients. Rural areas may have limited options.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Prescriptions:</strong> Prescriptions are filled at pharmacies (chemists). Many medications are government-subsidized at NZ$5 per item. Some medications that are over-the-counter elsewhere require prescription in NZ. Repeat prescriptions can often be managed online.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is health insurance mandatory for AEWV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No, it's not a visa requirement. However, work visa holders have limited public healthcare access and pay higher fees. Most AEWV holders get private insurance to avoid paying full price for GP visits and waiting months for specialist appointments. Immigration NZ "strongly recommends" it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's covered by ACC?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          ACC covers ALL accidents for everyone in New Zealand—citizens, residents, visa holders, even tourists. If you're injured in any accident (car crash, sports, workplace, tripping), treatment is covered. It also provides income replacement at 80% of salary. Illness is NOT covered—that's why you need health insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I get residence from AEWV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Green List Tier 1 occupations can apply for residence immediately upon arrival. Tier 2 occupations can apply after 2 years of work. Other occupations need to accumulate points through the Skilled Migrant Category (SMC) after 2+ years. Check if your role is on the Green List—it significantly speeds up residence.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on AEWV?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but you need a new job token from the new employer and apply for visa variation. The new employer must be accredited and complete their own Job Check. This takes 4-6 weeks typically. You can work for your current employer while the variation processes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my partner and children come with me?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your partner can apply for a Partnership-based Work Visa (open work rights). Dependent children can apply for dependent visas (study rights). They apply separately but are linked to your AEWV. Partner can work for any employer; children can attend school.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I lose my job?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          AEWV is employer-specific. If you lose your job, you have a grace period to find new employment and apply for visa variation. Immigration NZ recommends notifying them and finding a new accredited employer. You cannot simply work for a different employer without a new token.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The AEWV offers a clear pathway to working and eventually living in New Zealand—especially for Green List occupations. The employer accreditation system means legitimate employers with fair conditions, and the job check ensures you're paid properly. For tech workers, healthcare professionals, and engineers, the path to residence can be remarkably fast.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Health insurance isn't legally required, but it's practically essential. Work visa holders pay significantly more for public healthcare and face long waiting lists. Budget NZ$100-300/month for insurance—it's the cost of actual healthcare access in New Zealand. Many employers provide or subsidize coverage, so negotiate this in your offer.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The unique benefit of New Zealand is ACC—universal accident coverage for everyone. If you're injured in any accident, treatment is fully covered. This is unlike anywhere else in the world. Combined with private health insurance for illness, you get comprehensive protection. The lifestyle, work-life balance, and natural beauty make NZ compelling for those who can meet the salary threshold.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        AEWV requires an accredited employer and median wage salary (NZ$31.61/hour), with optional but strongly recommended private health insurance. ACC covers all accidents; insurance covers illness. Green List occupations get fast residence. New Zealand offers exceptional lifestyle for those who plan healthcare coverage properly.
      </p>
